The following 4 days of the vacation were spent in lessons, the days were long, exhausting, and painful. I had difficulty standing up, no difficulty falling back down, and at first was only able to fall left (which would mean unbinding and running across the run to start again on the right hand side). By the second day I was in so much pain that I told my instructor "if I fall over once more, I'm going to start crying", she responded "then don't fall over".

I persisted with lessons and by the fifth day I was able to traverse the easiest runs with the other members of the group, solidarity in the pain required to learn the sport had turned these people I barely knew, into my advisors, mentors and good mates. When I wasn't following the correct form, they'd let me know, when there was something I could improve, they'd suggest it, when I'd made apparent improvements, they'd congratulate me.

